  "text": "The LLVM IR Type System to Code Generation flow traces through the following key components:\n\n**1. LLVM IR Type Class Hierarchy (llvm/include/llvm/IR/Type.h, llvm/include/llvm/IR/DerivedTypes.h, llvm/lib/IR/Type.cpp):**\n\nThe Type class hierarchy starts with the base `Type` class that defines all LLVM types through a TypeID enum. Derived types are defined in DerivedTypes.h:\n- `IntegerType` (line 42 in DerivedTypes.h): Represents arbitrary bit-width integers with factory method IntegerType::get()\n- `FunctionType` (line 105): Represents function signatures with return type and parameter types\n- `StructType` (line 218): Represents structure types, supporting both literal (anonymous) and identified (named) structs\n\nThese types are created immutably and uniqued by LLVMContext. All primitive types (void, float, double, etc.) are stored as static members in LLVMContextImpl (Type.cpp lines 280-291).\n\n**2. Context Ownership and Type Uniquing (llvm/include/llvm/IR/LLVMContext.h, llvm/lib/IR/LLVMContextImpl.h, llvm/lib/IR/LLVMContext.cpp):**\n\nThe LLVMContext class acts as a container for the global type system state. It owns an opaque LLVMContextImpl that maintains:\n- Type uniquing tables: IntegerTypes (DenseMap, line 1759 in LLVMContextImpl.h), FunctionTypes (DenseSet with FunctionTypeKeyInfo, lines 1761-1762), AnonStructTypes and NamedStructTypes (lines 1763-1765)\n- The FunctionTypeKeyInfo (line 140 in LLVMContextImpl.h) and AnonStructTypeKeyInfo (line 93) structures define the comparison and hashing logic for type uniquing\n- A BumpPtrAllocator for allocating type objects\n\nFactory methods like IntegerType::get() (Type.cpp line 318) check the IntegerTypes map in C.pImpl->IntegerTypes and insert new types if not found. FunctionType::get() (line 368) uses FunctionTypeKeyInfo to uniquely identify and cache function types.\n\n**3. Type Lowering Pipeline (llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/*):**\n\nThe type lowering chain flows through:\n\na) **SelectionDAGBuilder** (SelectionDAGBuilder.h/cpp): Converts LLVM IR instructions to SelectionDAG nodes. It translates IR types to Extended Value Types (EVT)\n\nb) **SelectionDAG** (SelectionDAG.h/cpp, line 32): DAG representation uses EVT (ValueTypes.h line 35) which can represent both simple machine types (MVT) and extended types that don't fit in standard representations\n\nc) **DAGTypeLegalizer** (LegalizeTypes.h, line 31): Performs type legalization by:\n   - Converting types to target-legal equivalents\n   - Promoting small types to larger supported types\n   - Expanding large types into multiple smaller values\n   - Softening floating-point types to integer equivalents when needed\n\nThe type legalization uses TargetLowering (TargetLowering.h line 22) which specifies which ValueTypes are natively supported on the target architecture.\n\n**4. Machine Type Representation (llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/ValueTypes.h, llvm/include/llvm/CodeGenTypes/MachineValueType.h):**\n\nEVT (Extended Value Type, ValueTypes.h line 35) wraps MVT (Machine Value Type) from MachineValueType.h. MVT represents the actual machine types supported by the target (i8, i32, f64, v4i32, etc.).\n\n**5. Type Flow Summary:**\nIR Type → LLVMContext uniquing → Type::get*() factory methods → SelectionDAGBuilder → EVT → DAGTypeLegalizer → MVT (machine types) → SelectionDAGISel code generation\n\nThis architecture ensures type safety, memory efficiency through uniquing, and clean separation between IR-level and machine-level type representations."
